January 2024 Fundraising Report
Kel

Feb 1, 2024 ⋅  17 min read

Key Insights

  • Overall, deal volume trended slightly down month over month, though early-stage deals enjoyed a 68% increase month over month.
  • The biggest raises belonged to exchange Hashkey Group, bitcoin miners core Scientific and Canaan, social platform Freechat, and market-making desk Flowdesk.
  • Top deals of interest include Ingonyama’s, Polymer’s, DIMO, imgnAI, and Renzo.

Fundraising was slightly down as large, end of market deals slowed down in January. The largest deals were still dominated by exchanges and miners, with one upside surprise from Freechat, a WeChat-styled social app. As we will see, the type and range of raises expanded the earlier in stage we go.

Deal Trends by Investment Stage

As mentioned, most of the top-line decline has been driven by large post-IPO or strategic miner rounds decreasing in size. Seed through Series A deals enjoyed a large uptrend month over month in January:

  • +68% in MoM deal volume to $331 million paired with
  • +29% MoM growth in deal count to 53 total deals.

Walking through the bull + bear case for each of the major rounds:

Bagel Network

Bagel raised $3.1 million in pre-seed funding in a round led by Coinfund to build the data marketplace linking disparate datasets together with the end goal of cultivating one or more artificial general intelligences (AGIs).

The bull case

AI without financial attribution is untenable in the long run. Centralized platforms like OpenAI and others benefitted from the element of surprise, utilizing massive amounts of copyrighted data for which they are now being sued for billions. Going forward, users will likely demand compensation for the value they are driving. Bagel hops to be the linkage and attribution layer for data targeted towards AI training, which is expected to be a $13 billion industry by 2032 especially as industry use cases tend to granular fine-tuning versus utilizing out-of-the-box models like OpenAI's.

Add on that even the legendary AI researcher Andrej Karpathy has openly considered the merits of decentralization (alongside Elon Musk, no less), and the demand for decentralized AI is clear.

Source: X

The problem so far has been a lack of proper standards for interacting with AI onchain in any material manner, be it as a user, a seller of data, or otherwise. Given the terabytes of data that feed into AIs, Bagel’s approach (building the data marketplace from first principles) sounds like a high-value one if it works at scale.

Crypto is perfectly suited to address this problem, with Bagel aiming to create “a fair platform that respects the content rights of everyone involved and distribute benefits justly.”

The bear case:

The vision of a crypto-enhanced AI sounds great, but in practice, it’s tough to pull off. Vitalik just put out a piece outlining a lot of these technical challenges, which can be high-level-summarized as:

  • Computational Intensiveness: AI costs a lot of computing power. Techniques like encrypting AI model data with zero-knowledge proofs increase costs even further (although these can potentially be worked around)
  • Adversarial Machine Learning Attacks: AI models can be attacked through various methods, which are exacerbated by building AI on top of crypto rails.

Other risks include:

  • Integration risk: why this data marketplace over any other? Bagel seems to be technically sound, but they aren’t the only team with good tech: Nillion is one of surely many other examples. Moreover, this type of marketplace seems to be winner take most – should others compete on tech, BD, or branding better or quicker, the picture could become dicey.
  • Decentralized AI doesn’t take off: Tech history has many examples of product ideas that were too early for their time, even if ultimately right – see pets.com. Decentralized AI may be “too early” – if so, Bagel, in turn, could end up too early.

Liquid Re-Staking Token (LRT) Protocols: Renzo, Puffer

Renzo and Puffer both raised funding rounds, with Renzo raising $3.2 million in seed funding led by Maven11 Capital and Puffer raising a strategic round from Binance Labs.

The bull case: As the number of chains leveraging Ethereum for security increases, Eigenlayer restaking yields go up materially – causing more demand for liquid restaking tokens. Further demand will likely be sourced by lending protocols and exchanges, which may offer the opportunity to utilize restaking tokens as collateral throughout the world of centralized and decentralized crypto finance. All of that demand translates to TVL, which in turn translates to protocol revenues. Differences in protocol design may lead to markets favoring one over another, but the rising tide has and should continue to lift all boats.

The bear case: Restaking is almost sure to continue to grow in prominence as a narrative and reality within the ecosystem, but the market may trend towards winner take most for LRTs. If that’s the case, it’s ether.fi that has jumped out to a large early lead. The long tail of providers would still have some value in this scenario, but probably wouldn't yield venture scale returns if not at the #1 spot.

Then there’s the blowup risk. Much comment has been made about the perceived danger of rehypothecating economic stake to secure other chains. The concern here is that the effects of validator slashing events are multiplied when the same stake is used to validate N chains instead of just one like usual. In the low probability case of a major slashing event, it's likely that all restaking protocols would suffer significantly, as their collateral would be under risk of significant impairment.

Ingonyama

Ingonyama raised a $21m seed round led by IOSG, Walden Catalyst Ventures, and Geometry. Ingonyama (which means “lion" in Zulu) seeks to accelerate the creation of specialized hardware and software for zero-knowledge proofs. Prohibitive costs and relatively slow speeds are two of the biggest hurdles to ZK adoption – Ingonyama’s specialized chips aim to address those problems.

The bull case: Let’s start with a comparison. Bitmain (BTC mining) closed 2021 with 5+ billion dollars in revenues as the #1 bitcoin miner in the world. In the bull case for Ingonyama, the demand for zero-knowledge proofs in 2024 is where the demand for Bitcoin-specific ASICS was back in 2013, and will follow a similar trajectory from here on out.

In fact, given the broader set of chains and applications that could potentially be serviced by zero-knowledge proofs as opposed to Bitcoin Specific ASICs, the ZK prover market may be of even greater size than the bitcoin mining market. If Ingonyama’s chips solve for the prohibitive costs and relatively slow speeds the ZK market has had to deal with historically, and they do so in a way that consistently outperforms the competition, the “Bitmain of ZK” may be within reach.

The bear case: Ingonyama’s success hinges on two axes:

Differentiated Hardware: The capability to develop differentiated chips at scale faster than the competition will be key to the monetizability of hardware developed by Ingonyama. If any of those axes breaks down – the chips can’t be materially differentiated, or they can’t develop novel approaches fast enough, or they can’t scale production – their market becomes substantially less attractive. Additionally, it’s unclear to what extent the pricing power of the best ZK-specific chips will be at market maturity. Will it be tens of thousands of dollars, like Bitcoin miners today? Or will pricing power be lesser?

Monetizing Open Source Software: Ingonyama boasts an extensive library of tricks of the trade (dubbed “ICICLE”) that may well lead ZK acceleration research for years to come, but can they make any money off that? If not, it might end up being a money sink with great positive effects for the industry but unsustainably negative effects on the bottom line via high R&D costs.

Polymer

Polymer raised a $23 million Series A round led by Blockchain Capital, Maven 11, and Distributed Global to aid in their mission to bring the inter-blockchain communication protocol (IBC) to the Ethereum ecosystem.

The bull case: Polymer enhances interoperability between rollups via:

  • Enhanced security: IBC allows for maximally configurable security standards, from the highest grade (light client to light client) to quicker traditional options (multi-signature)
  • Neutrality: IBC is open-source tech with contributions from a wide number of communities. Its usage comes without any degree of vendor lock in, regardless of its scale of adoption – making it an attractive foundation for developers to build on top of.
  • Expanded feature set: When dozens, hundreds, or thousands of rollups are all connected via IBC, applications may employ interchain accounts and queries, allowing users to use one account to access N number of chains, reducing friction within the user experience and allowing application developers to more easily interoperate.

When the above is combined with upgrades like Dencun, we can see an endstate world where the sum of connected rollups – be it at Layer-2 or higher – approaches the performance and connectivity of integrated approaches used by chains like Solana, Monad, Sui, Sei, and Aptos.

In order for that world to be realized, a huge amount of transaction volume would have to flow through Polymer as the interoperability layer between chains, thus yielding Polymer validators an attractive source of persistent revenues.

The bear case: There’s a few reasons Polymer may not see the success we’ve outlined above:

  • Insufficient performance of the rollup ecosystem: Rollups may have an upper limit with respect to throughput and latency that’s uncompetitive compared to their integrated counterparties. Upgrades like Solana’s Firedancer, Sei v2, the deployment of Monad, and more could take integrated chains to five, six, or even seven figure transactions per second on extremely low latency times. It’s unclear if rollups will be able to meet that figure, even after accounting for the expanded data availability offered by DA layers like Eigenlayer and Monad.
  • Competitive market: IBC may be the best technology in the interoperability space, but other standards may win out for any number of reasons including, but not limited to: bridge speed, go to market speed, application integration advantages, liquidity, and more.
  • Lack of lock-in: Even if IBC wins out (favoring Polymer), it’s an open standard. Anyone can use it. Polymer is doing some more advanced stuff on the technical side to smooth out the process of integrating IBC for transfers across N number of chains, but it’s not certain whether or not these features are enough for rollups to choose Polymer consistently as opposed to deploying their own or competing solutions.

Hashkey Group

Hashkey group raised $100 million to expand its suite of crypto finance services, including their exchange and more.

The bull case: A simple one: exchanges print money on fees. Typically, certain exchanges dominate certain geographies, with higher volume locations usually worth more than lower volume ones. Hashkey operates out of Hong Kong, which certainly fits into the higher end of desirable locations for an exchange to dominate.

The bear case: Exchanges consolidate to winners take most at a global level, yielding the majority of market share to the biggest players like Coinbase and ByBit. This would leave a small pie for a large number of exchanges to engage in a knife fight over – not exactly the most bullish of scenarios.

Infrastructure Sector

The aforementioned Ingonyama deal is accompanied by a range of interesting deals in the infrastructure sector, including more BTC miner deals, new staking service providers, and a new DePIN deal.

BTC Miners: Core Scientific, Canaan

Core Scientific and Canaan raised $55 million and $50 million in strategic rounds, respectively. You may remember Core Scientific as one of the players who went bankrupt during the last cycle in the wake of Celsius and other Ce-DeFI lender failures.

The bull case: Miner resurgence on the back of BTC price action continues to signal investor confidence in continued BTC price appreciation as we start the new year. Should that trend continue, miner’s print more and more money. Simple enough.

The bear case: Mining is both highly competitive and highly reliant on appreciating bitcoin prices. Any rising hardware costs or BTC price declines will put large amounts of pressure on these businesses, hampering their probability of success.

Kiln

Kiln raised $17 million to accelerate the adoption of their enterprise staking as a service solutions.

The bull case: Somewhat similar to bitcoin miners, validator service providers print money by maintaining Layer-1 networks. The difference here is that validator service providers typically manage large amounts of other people’s stake, taking a fee of the staking rewards they earn. The advantage of this approach is at least two-fold: potentially lower costs as platforms like Kiln can leverage other people’s capital to accelerate earnings, and diversification of earnings via validation of multiple Proof-of-Stake smart contract networks.

The bear case: Staking services can become somewhat commoditized as advanced enterprise users have a plethora of options in addition to the ability to stake for themselves. Market margins may be too compressed to build out venture scale businesses in this market as a result.

DIMO

DIMO raised $11.5 million led by Coinfund to further their goal of collecting the world’s auto data using decentralized physical infrastructure. The market for automotive data is projected to increase from about 2 billion today to 10 to 20 billion by 2030.

The bull case: Incentivizing car owners to plug into DIMO’s network gives them a persistent edge in automobile data, just as the world trends towards potentially more data-rich vehicles (electric, internet connected, and potentially self-driving). As a result, DIMO gains large market share of valuable automobile data, selling that on to other businesses like car manufacturers.

The bear case: Either people aren’t incentivized to plug into the DIMO network, or the car data they can acquire isn’t worth as much as it costs in hardware development and token incentives.

Financial Sector

The financial sector saw the first market maker focused deal in a long time accompany a Swiss crypto bank as the highlights, mixed in with the usual flow of exchanges, as well as a custodial deal. Generally, these deals have more straightforward bull or bear cases as opposed to their more technical counterparts.

Flowdesk

Flowdesk Raised $50 million to further their OTC trading and market making services stack.

The bull case: In bullish market conditions, demand for liquidity from both OTC sales and exchange-based market making skyrockets. Given the illiquidity and informational asymmetry of these markets, market makers can – and often do – run up immense profits as a result of their operations.

The bear case: Operating these platforms often involves convoluted, so-called “daisy chains of borrowers and lenders” which take out everyone involved in the event of explosion. Often found in the wreckage of such explosions are market makers due to the leveraged nature of their business. Proper risk management goes a long way to avoiding this outcome, but with interconnected, hyper-correlated profits so high, many market makers – Flowbank or otherwise – will find themselves enjoying a life similar to the 1000 days in the life of a Thanksgiving turkey: a steady ascent of enjoyment, followed by the sudden onslaught of decline.

Sygnum Bank

Sygnum Bank raised $40 million from Azimut to grow its Swiss-based banking operations.

The bull case: In bull markets, the prospective clientele of a crypto bank expands drastically. With fairly limited options, there’s room for a new bank to wedge its way into the market.

The bear case: Even if the market continues the bullish trend from Q4, it’s possible that crypto banking demand doesn’t increase enough for new players, due to the emergence of onchain “banking” options as well as big exchanges acting as defacto banks.

Dojoswap

Dojoswap raised $25 million in a public token sale to launch their Injective-based AMM.

The bull case: Continued success for the Injective ecosystem increases the likelihood that native projects succeed. Dojoswap could be the native exchange of the Injective ecosystem.

The bear case: Injective is still largely unproven as an ecosystem – its longevity is completely uncertain as of now. Moreover, even if Injective succeeds, other bigger DEXs from other ecosystems could come in and dominate market share due to users' existing familiarity with those platforms.

Cryptosafe

Cryptosafe raised $20 million to continue the build out of their crowdfunding and portfolio tooling platform.

The bull case: Launchpads are very popular within crypto. Horizontally integrating launchpad tools with portfolio visualization, charting, and trading tools could be an unlock in UX that allows Cryptosafe to enter into an otherwise hotly-contested market.

The bear case: The interface layer of crypto is the knifiest of knife fights, with a huge number of entrenched players at the global and ecosystem-specific layers. The same goes for the launchpad space. Putting the two together may not be enough for CryptoSafe to carve out space in the market.

Finoa

Finoa raised $15 million to further the adoption of their crypto custody business.

The bull case: Bull markets catalyze the increase of existing crypto institutional capital as well as bringing new players into the market. That should mean plenty of demand for custodians like Finoa, as institutions can’t exactly run millions of client funds off of browser-based hot wallet solutions.

The bear case: It’s unclear how much of a moat there is around custodial services, except maybe around brand. Finoa can build up that brand over time, but it’s not clear to me how long that takes from an institutional perspective when compared to existing custodial options like Anchorage and BitGo.

Consumer Sector

Consumer saw a surprisingly large deal in the social space from Freechat, just as excitement on another social protocol, Farcaster, lights up. We also saw the return of music NFTs and a few AI deals on the fundraising scene.

Social projects: Freechat and DeSo

Freechat raised $80 million, and DeSo raised $20 million to accelerate the adoption of their social messaging platforms.

The bull case: We’ve been trying to crack the crypto social media code for some time. Whichever app can do it will end up with some combination of the micro-monetization of Web2 social via advertisements and the high-skew average revenue per user offered by crypto users who spend big.

That’s got to be worth something.

The bear case: Go to market is crucial in the social space. Freechat seems to be geared as a sort of WeChat competitor focused on the Chinese market. In the case of DeSo, it’s unclear how the FOCUS platform will differ from their existing platform, which hasn’t seen much success to date. In both cases, should their approach not work out, pivoting will be difficult. There are just too many Web3 competitors taking every approach within every ecosystem possible.

Tune.Fm

Tune.Fm raised $20 million led by LDA capital to support the adoption of their music NFT based streaming platform.

The bull case: Music streaming platforms have long been criticized for excessive take rates. NFT-based streaming protocols can cut out middlemen, undercut costs, and, in turn, win market share.

The bear case: Streaming platforms are power law distributed. New platforms will struggle to break into the market, even with theoretically superior tech stacks and fairer value distribution.

A bigger slice of royalty pie in Web3 doesn’t mean much if the size of the overall pie is significantly smaller than the pie of royalties on web2 platforms.

WaveBL

WaveBL raised $11 million to support its electronic document transmission protocol.

The bull case: Document fraud cost people over $8 billion in 2022. A protocol by which documents are signed using cryptographic keys verifiably tied to distinct identities would largely eliminate this problem – in turn generating value for the producers of said protocol.

The bear case: This seems more of a BD game than a tech game, as it only scales if very legit players like big businesses or even governments adopt it. In other words, it’s more likely to skew towards a top-down, B2B approach rather than scaling from the ground up. Businesses and governments are a lot slower to adopt changing standards compared to incentivized degenerates, so this may pose an insurmountable challenge for the WaveBL team.

imgnAI

imgnAI raised $1.6 million from Hack VC to further their image generation platform for creators.

The bull case: The socialization and incentivization of image generation unlocks better model training, giving imgnAI an edge over other image generation platforms reliant on centralized parties. User inflows create a robust platform around the core primitive of incentivizes – call it an Instagram for AI-generated photographs, with a token.

The bear case: Incentivized image generation leads to poisoned models due to poor incentive alignment. Social “users” aren’t real users, but token farm and dumpers. In sum, the introduction of a token turns out to be a useless or even net-negative proposition.

Concluding Thoughts

The fundraising landscape is getting interesting. What crypto needs now is experimentation at the application layer, so that people will use all of the impressive infrastructure we’ve created over the years. If January 2024 is any indication for the year ahead, tons of experimentation will to come throughout 2024.
